doc
  Test provides assertion helpers for `test` declarations.

  `assert` fails immediately via `Fail String`. `check` accumulates
  failures and continues — the test runner counts them via a thread-local
  counter that is reset after each test case.
effect Fail E
  doc
    Abort the current computation with an error payload.

      Fail.fail("boom")
  fn fail(error: E) -> Never

doc
  Accumulate non-fatal check results within a test case.

  Unlike `Fail`, `check` continues execution after a failure so that all
  assertions in a test body are evaluated.  The test runner reads the
  accumulated failure count after the case returns.
effect Test
  doc
    Record whether a boolean check passed.

      Test.check(1 == 1)
  fn check(passed: Bool) -> Unit
  doc
    Record whether a boolean check passed, with a custom message printed on failure.

      Test.check_with_message(1 == 2, "one should equal two")
  fn check_with_message(passed: Bool, message: String) -> Unit

doc
  Assert a condition, failing with a default message when false.

    Test.assert(true)    -- => ()
pub fn assert(value: Bool) -[Fail String]> Unit
  if value
    ()
  else
    Fail.fail("assertion failed")

doc
  Assert a condition with a custom failure message.

    Test.assert_with_message(1 == 2, "math broke")   -- => Fail("math broke")
pub fn assert_with_message(value: Bool, message: String) -[Fail String]> Unit
  if value
    ()
  else
    Fail.fail(message)
